  "prompt": "What is a doppelganger? What are some examples?",
  "response": "A doppelganger is a look-alike or double of a living person, often with a supernatural or eerie connotation. The term originates from German, literally meaning \"double-walker.\" Here are some key points and examples:\n\nDefinition:\n- A person who closely resembles another person\n- In folklore, often considered an evil or ghostly twin\n- Sometimes believed to be a harbinger of bad luck or death\n\nTypes of Doppelgangers:\n1. Unrelated people who look strikingly similar\n2. Mythological/supernatural doubles\n3. Coincidental look-alikes\n\nReal-world Examples:\n- Actor Michael Cera and actor Jesse Eisenberg\n- Actors Elijah Wood and Tobey Maguire\n- Actors Matt Damon and Mark Wahlberg\n\nHistorical/Fictional Examples:\n- Edgar Allan Poe wrote about doppelgangers in his stories\n- Finnish folklore suggests seeing your own doppelganger means imminent death\n- Some historical figures claimed to have seen their own double\n\nFamous Claims:\n- Abraham Lincoln reportedly saw his own doppelganger in a mirror\n- Queen Elizabeth I was said to have seen her own double before her death\n\nModern examples often include celebrity look-alikes or people who discover their uncanny resemblance through social media or chance encounters.",
